Framing the Problem

My goal is to conduct a Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) between the dependent variable (median_house_value) and each of the following independent variables (median_income, population and households). Based on the findings, I will select the model that provides the best fit.

In[2]:
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split 
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error

In[3]:
## using kagglehub to get the dataset and zipfile to unzip it
import kagglehub
import zipfile

path = kagglehub.dataset_download("camnugent/california-housing-prices", path='housing.csv')

## extracts the csv file to a folder inside the environment called dataset
with zipfile.ZipFile(path, "r") as zip_ref:
    zip_ref.extractall("dataset") 

## read csv file using pandas
housing_df = pd.read_csv("dataset/housing.csv")

Variables used for the analysis:

Median House Value (median_house_value)
  • Meaning: Median cost of the households within a block.
  • Range: Varies between minimum of $14,999 and maximum of $500,001.
  • Characteristics:
    • Measured in US dollars.
    • Continuous numerical variable.
    • The maximum value may indicate the presence of outliers in the data.
    • Dependent variable used in the analysis to examine the relationship with the other independent variables.
Median Income (median_income)
  • Meaning: Median income for househodls within a block of houses.
  • Range: Varies between minimum of $49,990 dollars and maximum of $1,5 million dollars.
  • Characteristics:
    • Measured in tens of thousands of US dollars.
Population (population)
  • Meaning: Total number of people that live within a block of houses.
  • Range: Varies between minimum of 300 people and maximum of 3,6 million people.
  • Characteristics:
    • The maximum population seems to suggest an outlier due to the unusually high value.
Number of households (households)
  • Meaning: Total number of households (group of people) that live within a block of houses.
  • Range: Varies between minimum of 100 households and maximum of 608,200 households.
  • Characteristics:
    • The maximum number of households may indicate an outlier due to the unusually high value.

## plot median house value vs. median income
income_scatterplot = sns.scatterplot(x="median_income", y="median_house_value", data=housing_df)
income_scatterplot.set_title("Median house value vs. median income")
Out[5]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Median house value vs. median income')

There seems to be a weak but positive relationship between the median house value and the median income of the population sample. Most data points are clustered together between 2 and 8 thousands for median income.

As the median income increases, the median value of the house tends to rise as well. However, the scattered data points suggest variability, indicating a lot of noise in the data. Additionally, there are outliers on the top of the distribution, which suggests that the dataset needs to be processed before conducting a linear regression.

Since the relationship between the variables is weak, a linear regression may not provide a good fit to the data.

In[6]:

This plot indicates that changes in the median house value do not affect the population size. Since the data points are clustered at the left side of the plot, it indicates a weak to non-existent relationship between population size and median house value, with considerable noise in the data.

Because there doesn't seem to be any observable trend, we may need to look into other factors that would be more meaningful for conducting a linear regression.

Fitting models - Linear regression

Data preprocessing: We observed earlier in the visualizations that the median house value has outliers that constrict us from conducting a linear regression. Therefore, we need to remove these extreme values before continuing.

In[8]:
housing_df_preprocessed = housing_df[housing_df.median_house_value != 500001]

The dependent variable (y) would be the same for all three regression models.

In[9]:
y = housing_df_preprocessed[["median_house_value"]]

Model 1: median house value vs. median income

  1. Train and test split

    We'll split our dataset into training and testing, the first 80% of the data will be used for training and the rest of 20% for testing. We set the random_state to 0 because we want the split to be different everytime.

In[10]:
X_income = housing_df_preprocessed[["median_income"]]
X_train_income, X_test_income, y_train_income, y_test_income = train_test_split(X_income, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

  1. Train the model

    We'll use the sklearn.linear_model.LinearRegression to fit the model on the training data.

In[11]:
model1 = LinearRegression()
model1.fit(X_train_income, y_train_income)
Out[11]:
LinearRegression()

  1. Evaluate the model

    We'll make predictions using the training set, then calculate the Mean Squared Error (MSE) and the Mean Absolute Error (MAE).

In[12]:
y_pred_income = model1.predict(X_train_income)

## Calculate errors
train_mse_income = mean_squared_error(y_train_income, y_pred_income)
train_mae_income = mean_absolute_error(y_train_income, y_pred_income)

Now, we'll do the same for the other two models.

Model 2: median house value vs. population

In[19]:
# 1. Train and test split
X_population = housing_df_preprocessed[["population"]]
X_train_population, X_test_population, y_train_population, y_test_population = train_test_split(X_population, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

# 2. Train the model
model2 = LinearRegression()
model2.fit(X_train_population, y_train_population)

# 3. Evaluate the model
# Make predictions
y_pred_population = model2.predict(X_train_population)

## Calculate errors
train_mse_population = mean_squared_error(y_train_population, y_pred_population)
train_mae_population = mean_absolute_error(y_train_population, y_pred_population)

Model 3: median house value vs. number of households

In[14]:
# 1. Train and test split
X_households = housing_df_preprocessed[["households"]]
X_train_households, X_test_households, y_train_households, y_test_households = train_test_split(X_households, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

# 2. Train the model
model3 = LinearRegression()
model3.fit(X_train_households, y_train_households)

# 3. Evaluate the model
# Make predictions
y_pred_households = model3.predict(X_train_households)

## Calculate errors
train_mse_households = mean_squared_error(y_train_households, y_pred_households)
train_mae_households = mean_absolute_error(y_train_households, y_pred_households)

Regression model comparison: Intercept, slope, MAE, and MSE

In[15]:
## Model 1 = median house value vs median income
## Model 2 = median house value vs population
## Model 3 = median house value vs number of households
regression_models = {
    "Model": ["Model 1", "Model 2", "Model 3"],
    "y-intercept": [model1.intercept_[0], model2.intercept_[0], model3.intercept_[0]],
    "slope": [model1.coef_[0][0], model2.coef_[0][0], model3.coef_[0][0]],
    "MAE": [train_mae_income, train_mae_population, train_mae_households],
    "MSE": [train_mse_income, train_mse_population, train_mse_households]
}

df_models = pd.DataFrame(regression_models)

Regression Model 1: median house value vs. median income

In[16]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))

text = '\n'.join((
        r"y-intercept = %.3f" % model1.intercept_[0],
        r"slope = %.3f" % model1.coef_[0][0],
        r"MAE = %.3f" %  train_mae_income,
        r"MSE = %.3f" % train_mse_income))
props = dict(boxstyle='round', facecolor='lightblue', alpha=0.5)

ax.scatter(X_train_income, y_train_income, edgecolors='white')
ax.plot(X_train_income, y_pred_income, color='red')
ax.text(0.01, 0.98, text, transform=ax.transAxes, verticalalignment='top', bbox=props)

ax.set_title("Regression Model 1: Median house value vs. median income (training)")
ax.set_xlabel("Median Income (tens of thousands of dollars)")
ax.set_ylabel("Median House Value (dollars)")

plt.show()

We observe a moderate positive correlation between the median house value and median income, as indicated by the slope of 4.03. This means that for every $10,000 increase in median income, the house prices increase by $40,000.

The intercept further tells us that the base median house prices fall around $44,500 thousand dollars even when the median income is zero.

The Mean Absolute Error (MAE) indicates that the predictions deviate from the actual house values by $56,700, suggesting that our model is not very accurate.

Since Mean Squared Error (MSE) is larger than MAE, we can conclude that outliers are affecting our model.

Interestingly, Model 3 has the highest slope of 24.76, which suggests a strong correlation between the median house value and the number of households. This means that an increase of $1,000 in the median house price can lead to an increase of 24,000 households per block.

The intercept value tells us that the base median house prices fall around $180,000 when the number of households is zero.

Despite the strong correlation between the variables, the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of 77,694 indicates that the predictions deviate from the actual values by $77,694, which makes this model less accurate than Model 1.

Since Mean Squared Error (MSE) is larger than MAE, we can conclude that outliers are affecting our model.

Summary

Based on the Exploratory Component Analysis conducted, Model 1 is the best fit because it has the lowest Mean Absolute Error (MAE) as well as the lowest Mean Squared Error (MSE). This tells us that the predictions of Model 1 are closer to the actual values compared to the other models.

Although Model 3 has the highest slope, the high value of of MAE indicate that its predictions are less accurate. Similarly, Model 2 has the weakest correlation and also the highest error values, which makes it the least effective model.
